> In the hotel case, both containers would need to adhere to a strict standard.

In the hotel case it will adhere to a standard, as you mentioned, it is a required for the system to work. We just haven't written / formalized that standard. Even though for cross platform hotel sharing all device OEM provisioning information will need to be included in the invite each OEM will only parse / read their own Information. The sender will simply be a pass through of the OEM data from the partner to the recipient.

> I would advocate putting all provisioning material into the genericData as that is the only field the format is currently coupled with. Otherwise, I think it weaken the standard and sets a precedent for coupling format to additional fields on the top level.

This is why I'm not a huge fan of the including `genericData` in this spec.

If we think having format defined top level keys will weaken the standard what do you think about having `format` and `content` (name WIP) as the only two top level keys. And then all credential transfer information would live inside content. i.e.:

```
{
	"format" : "digitalwallet.carkey.ccc"
	"content": {
	    "genericSharingData": {
	        // ...
	    },
	    "appleSharingData": { ... },
	    "androidSharingData": { ... },
	}
}
```

Then if we wanted to add new top level keys to the IETF standard there would be no risk that those keys collide with the keys used in the various format specs. For example, we could add a `messageIdentifier` field to the IETF spec.

> I think my reservation here is mixing a container for proprietary use with provisioning information. Forcing a standardization on a container meant for proprietary use kind of defeats its nature.

I agree with this, although I don't feel very strongly about it. I see the benefit in separating true proprietary or secret sauce keys from device OEM opaque blobs; where even though the contents of the blob is opaque all device OEMs know that the blob is effectively a bearer token.

Since we are settled on "format" + "content" I think this discussion doesn't need to block this PR. I'll added this discussion to the agenda next week.

---

I was thinking it would work like:

```
{
   "format": "digitalwallet.hotelkey.hyatt",
   "content": {
      "appleHotelData": {  ... },
      "androidHotelData": {  ... },
      // Device OEM Proprietary Containers
      "appleSharingData": {  ... },
      "androidSharingData": {  ... },
      "xxxSharingData": {  ... }
   }
}
```

That way there is no risk of future EITF spec changes introducing new top level keys that collide with proprietary fields. But since the usage of "appleSharingData" / "androidSharingData" is up to each device OEM the data could be put anywhere.

```suggestion
    "format" : "digitalwallet.carkey.ccc",
    "content": { 
        // Format specific fields
    }
```

